			<section id="content">
				
				<div class="top-title">
					<img width="1400" height="400" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/top-img5.jpg" class="attachment-page-featured wp-post-image" alt="top-img5" />					<h2 class="animate fadeIn">U.S. Chamber of Commerce</h2>
				</div><!-- /.top-title -->

				<div class="sections">									<div class="section-text_image white-row">
										<div class="shell">
											<div class="text-holder left">
												<h5>PROJECT BRIEF</h5>
<h2>Redesigning An Institution</h2>
<p>The U.S. Chamber of Commerce – which represents the interests of millions of U.S. businesses in Washington D.C. – wanted to reinvent their online identity. They chose NAV to create a new website that would take their brand and pro-business agenda into the future.</p>
											</div>
											<img width="542" height="285" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/border-img.jpg" class="right bordered" alt="border-img" />											<div class="cl">&nbsp;</div>
										</div><!-- /.shell -->
									</div>
																		<div class="section-image_text white-row">
										<div class="shell">
											<div class="text-holder right">
												<p>We developed the “Meet the Chamber” campaign to reintroduce the organization to the public and create a lasting identity and platform that will help the Chamber fulfill their mission, engaging with businesses, government and the public. More than a facelift, the new website would breathe new life into this hundred-year-old organization.</p>
											</div>
											<img width="642" height="450" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/img1.jpg" class="left " alt="img1" />											<div class="cl">&nbsp;</div>
										</div><!-- /.shell -->
									</div>
																		<div class="section-boxes gray-row">
										<div class="shell">
											<div class="left-box left">
												<h3>Conversations, Interviews, User Personas &amp; Research</h3>
<p>NAV began by meeting with Chamber staff to ask questions and nail down style and tone, then performed dozens of in-person interviews with staff and site users. We learned that the original site, built to mimic the Chamber’s internal organization, was not helping people find the quotes, facts, advocacy tools and messaging they were seeking.</p>
											</div><!-- /.left-box -->
											<div class="right-box right">
												<img width="779" height="224" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/img2-779x224.jpg" class="attachment-section-middle" alt="img2" 0="" />												<div class="left-part left">
													<p>Yes, the chief complaint of Chamber site visitors was that they simply couldn’t find what they were looking for. By observing people using the site, we saw that the most advanced users knew how to find things by rote, rather than reason. The new site must make thousands of pages of content easily and intuitively accessible to the Chamber’s membership, the public, the press and the government.</p>
												</div>
												<div class="right-part right">
																											<div class="light-box">
															<div class="inner">
																<h4>Is it easy to find things on the site?</h4>
															</div><!-- /.inner -->
														</div>
													
																											<div class="dark-box">
															<div class="inner">
																<h2>No.</h2>
															</div><!-- /.inner -->
														</div>
													
													<p><strong>94.6%</strong> OF STAKEHOLDERS</p>
												</div>
											</div><!-- /.right-box -->
											<div class="cl">&nbsp;</div>
										</div><!-- /.shell -->
									</div>
																		<div class="section-image_text white-row">
										<div class="shell">
											<div class="text-holder right">
												<h3>Information Architecture</h3>
<p>Next, we turned the tables to look at the site from the perspective of the users, creating user personas to explore the needs of the Chamber’s diverse audience. We examined the analytics to determine how people were using the site, what they were looking for and how they were getting there. From here, we drafted a new site navigation and tested it with real people to see if it was now easier for them to complete their tasks.</p>
											</div>
											<img width="639" height="632" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/img3.jpg" class="left " alt="img3" />											<div class="cl">&nbsp;</div>
										</div><!-- /.shell -->
									</div>
																		<div class="section-slider gray-row">
										<div class="shell">
											<h3 class="left">Designing The Timeline</h3>
											<div class="slide-pag">
												<ul>
													<li><a href="#">Sketch</a></li><li><a href="#">Digital Sketch</a></li><li><a href="#">Wireframe</a></li><li><a href="#">UI Design</a></li><li><a href="#">Final</a></li>												</ul>
											</div><!-- /.slide-pag -->
											<div class="cl">&nbsp;</div>
											<div class="slider">
												<ul class="slides">
													<li><img width="1185" height="441" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/slide1.jpg" class="attachment-section-slider" alt="slide1" /></li><li><img width="1185" height="441" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/slide2.jpg" class="attachment-section-slider" alt="slide2" /></li><li><img width="1185" height="441" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/slide3.jpg" class="attachment-section-slider" alt="slide3" /></li><li><img width="1185" height="441" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/slide4.jpg" class="attachment-section-slider" alt="slide4" /></li><li><img width="1185" height="441" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/slide5.jpg" class="attachment-section-slider" alt="slide5" /></li>												</ul><!-- /.slides -->
											</div><!-- /.slider -->

																							<div class="text-holder2 left">
													<p>But how best to surface thousands of pages of content developed over years? To keep it clean and intuitive, NAV developed the “Timeline” concept so that people can quickly home in on the information they need. Through the visual timeline, users select a top-level issue and then move around within it by date or by selecting and searching on more specific criteria. This puts the Chamber’s wealth of resources at people’s fingertips, while not overwhelming them with navigation that isn’t relevant in the moment. </p>
												</div><!-- /.text-holder2 -->
											
																					</div>
									</div>
																		<div class="section-text_image white-row">
										<div class="shell">
											<div class="text-holder left">
												<h3>Visual Design</h3>
<p>We wanted to move away from a bureaucratic “inside the Beltway” aesthetic and design a welcoming environment to help people make an emotional connection with the Chamber. Photography, color, iconography and other visual elements were used to create the feeling of a room full of colleagues, rather than a large and faceless organization.</p>
<p>Using the principles of responsive design, the site display changes automatically to accommodate whatever device a person is using. So, tablet and phone views are different from a desktop computer, while providing the same level of experience.</p>
											</div>
											<img width="536" height="536" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/circle-img.png" class="right rounded" alt="circle-img" />											<div class="cl">&nbsp;</div>
										</div><!-- /.shell -->
									</div>
																		<div class="section-image_text gray-row">
										<div class="shell">
											<div class="text-holder right">
												<h3>Technical Design</h3>
<p>Then we brought the visual design to life, coding the front end of the site and all user interactions, working with technical partners to bring the front and back-end elements together in Drupal – the open-source content management system selected for its ability to grow and adapt with the Chamber.</p>
<p>“Buttons invite you to click, getting softer as you move over them. These interactions are where design really comes to life.” – Mike Aleo, NAV</p>
											</div>
											<img width="560" height="539" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/img4.jpg" class="left " alt="img4" />											<div class="cl">&nbsp;</div>
										</div><!-- /.shell -->
									</div>
																		<div class="section-isotope white-row">
										<div class="shell">
											<div id="container">
												<div class="item larger"><img width="782" height="652" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/item1.jpg" class="attachment-section-isotope-larger" alt="item1" /></div><div class="item small"><img width="381" height="316" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/item4.jpg" class="attachment-section-isotope-small" alt="item4" /></div><div class="item small"><img width="381" height="316" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/chamber11-381x316.jpg" class="attachment-section-isotope-small" alt="chamber1" /></div><div class="item small"><img width="381" height="316" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/chamber2-381x316.jpg" class="attachment-section-isotope-small" alt="chamber2" /></div><div class="item small"><img width="381" height="316" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/item5.jpg" class="attachment-section-isotope-small" alt="item5" /></div><div class="item small"><img width="381" height="316" src="http://nav.co/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/item6.jpg" class="attachment-section-isotope-small" alt="item6" /></div>											</div><!-- /#container -->
										</div>
									</div>
																		<div class="section-2_columns white-row">
										<div class="shell">
											<div class="row">
																									<h3>Finish Line</h3>
																								<div class="text-holder left">
													<p>And there you have it. The new Chamber website serves the interests of the Chamber by putting the needs of their site visitors first. A warm welcome and intelligent organization work together to create a smooth experience for the people who rely on the Chamber, enabling them to accomplish more.</p>
<p>For us, it has been an incredibly challenging and rewarding project. The Chamber team brought commitment, high expectations and a great degree of design and technical sophistication to the table. By engaging NAV to create a new website that focuses on the needs of their users, the Chamber seized this opportunity, creating a bold new digital experience that will propel the organization forward.</p>
												</div><!-- /.text-holder -->
												<div class="right-text right">
																											<a href="http://uschamber.com" class="blue-btn"><span>View the live site</span></a>
													
